<p><strong>Neil<br /></strong>Well I did tell you to kill time, but I didn't mean destroy a clock. In English, when you say you are 'killing time', it means you are doing something that isn't really important just to occupy yourself before the start of your next plan or arrangement.</p> 
<p><strong>Helen<br /></strong>Yeah, that's right. Killing time has nothing to do with violence towards clocks. It's an expression which means to do something which isn't really important just to keep you occupied until the start of your next plan or arrangement. Here are some examples.</p> 
<p><strong>Examples</strong></p> 
<p><em>I turned up an hour early for my flight, so I just looked at the duty free to kill some time.</em></p> 
<p><em>I had an hour between work and meeting my friends so I killed time in a department store.</em></p> 
<p><em>I always arrive hours early for job interviews. I'd rather have to kill time than deal with the stress of being late!</em></p> 
